00:47:27,717 --> 00:47:28,938
[SPEAKER_12]: Good afternoon, everybody.

541
00:47:28,958 --> 00:47:30,240
[SPEAKER_12]: I am Teresa Dupont.

542
00:47:30,280 --> 00:47:32,942
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm the Community Preservation Manager for the City of Medford.

543
00:47:32,962 --> 00:47:37,266
[SPEAKER_12]: I also, in my role, staff support the Historic District Commission.

544
00:47:37,766 --> 00:47:44,473
[SPEAKER_12]: So I am just going to share a quick overview of what goes into establishing a historic district as we continue these conversations.

545
00:47:45,353 --> 00:47:49,077
[SPEAKER_12]: It would be good for folks to be aware of what the process looks like.

546
00:47:50,787 --> 00:47:52,168
[SPEAKER_12]: Um, so actually, let me back up here.

547
00:47:52,328 --> 00:47:58,251
[SPEAKER_12]: So, just as a quick overview, because I'm now timing myself, because we are at 7, we want to be ready at 7 o'clock.

548
00:47:58,631 --> 00:48:01,213
[SPEAKER_12]: So, just as a quick overview, what is the historic district commission review?

549
00:48:01,233 --> 00:48:02,433
[SPEAKER_12]: What is within their purview?

550
00:48:03,274 --> 00:48:06,756
[SPEAKER_12]: We are tasked with, and it's all Medford residents, all volunteers.

551
00:48:07,396 --> 00:48:10,378
[SPEAKER_12]: We are tasked with reviewing any sort of renovation project.

552
00:48:11,118 --> 00:48:12,760
[SPEAKER_12]: And it only pertains to the exterior.

553
00:48:12,780 --> 00:48:15,623
[SPEAKER_12]: We have no jurisdiction or purview of an interior of a property.

554
00:48:15,663 --> 00:48:18,826
[SPEAKER_12]: It's only things that are visible from the public right of way.

555
00:48:18,846 --> 00:48:21,208
[SPEAKER_12]: If we're standing in front of the property, what can we see?

556
00:48:21,228 --> 00:48:23,410
[SPEAKER_12]: And that usually includes architectural features.

557
00:48:23,450 --> 00:48:29,797
[SPEAKER_12]: This is going to be like your gingerbread moldings, your columns, you know, like those special things that make a property historic.

558
00:48:30,678 --> 00:48:33,420
[SPEAKER_12]: Windows and doors, it doesn't include storm doors or windows.

559
00:48:34,694 --> 00:48:38,419
[SPEAKER_12]: Siding and fencing, retaining walls, and chimneys.

560
00:48:38,719 --> 00:48:42,284
[SPEAKER_12]: So just as a quick overview, this is what the purview of the district is.

561
00:48:42,864 --> 00:48:49,673
[SPEAKER_12]: I also want to plug that we're always looking for new members, so if folks are interested in applying, scan the QR code or head over to the city's website.

562
00:48:51,481 --> 00:48:55,204
[SPEAKER_12]: So, the timeline here as an overview, it is a lengthy timeline.

563
00:48:55,224 --> 00:48:56,945
[SPEAKER_12]: It is not something that can be rushed through.

564
00:48:57,185 --> 00:48:59,947
[SPEAKER_12]: And I will say this a couple of times during this presentation.

565
00:48:59,987 --> 00:49:02,549
[SPEAKER_12]: The important thing is to have buy in.

566
00:49:04,110 --> 00:49:07,492
[SPEAKER_12]: The most successful district implementation is when there is buy in from all stakeholders.

567
00:49:08,533 --> 00:49:11,374
[SPEAKER_12]: So let's talk about from our first step here.

568
00:49:11,414 --> 00:49:12,955
[SPEAKER_12]: It's really the project preparation.

569
00:49:13,055 --> 00:49:20,318
[SPEAKER_12]: This includes some rigorous engagement with the property owners, the folks that would be most affected by this district implementation.

570
00:49:20,378 --> 00:49:22,319
[SPEAKER_12]: So we always start with an opinion survey.

571
00:49:22,339 --> 00:49:24,299
[SPEAKER_12]: It is online as well as in print.

572
00:49:25,360 --> 00:49:31,822
[SPEAKER_12]: We hold at least one, but usually several public information meetings because we want to make sure that we're reaching every single person.

573
00:49:32,743 --> 00:49:33,603
[SPEAKER_12]: These are public meetings.

574
00:49:33,623 --> 00:49:34,944
[SPEAKER_12]: Anybody from the public can join.

575
00:49:35,824 --> 00:49:42,330
[SPEAKER_12]: While we're doing that, we're also beginning what the vehicle that is called by the state the preliminary study report.

576
00:49:42,670 --> 00:49:45,493
[SPEAKER_12]: We bring in a historic consultant to conduct this work.

577
00:49:46,113 --> 00:49:47,474
[SPEAKER_12]: It starts with an introduction.

578
00:49:48,075 --> 00:49:53,380
[SPEAKER_12]: Why are we looking at a district in this particular section of the city?

579
00:49:53,400 --> 00:49:58,704
[SPEAKER_12]: The methodology behind ascertaining this specific portion of the city.

580
00:49:58,784 --> 00:50:01,247
[SPEAKER_12]: What the significance of the historical significance

581
00:50:02,193 --> 00:50:03,594
[SPEAKER_12]: and justifying our boundaries.

582
00:50:03,634 --> 00:50:07,555
[SPEAKER_12]: Why are we selecting certain properties to be within this district?

583
00:50:07,915 --> 00:50:15,258
[SPEAKER_12]: That portion of it, again, rigorous engagement with the affected property owners can be three to six months, typically leans more on the six month side.

584
00:50:16,123 --> 00:50:19,547
[SPEAKER_12]: From there, we're taking that study and we're continuing to work on it.

585
00:50:19,587 --> 00:50:24,654
[SPEAKER_12]: But once we're at a draft point, it gets submitted to the state's historical commission.

586
00:50:24,674 --> 00:50:26,596
[SPEAKER_12]: It's called the Massachusetts Historical Commission.

587
00:50:27,658 --> 00:50:32,464
[SPEAKER_12]: We also do submit it to the Community Development Board for any review and comments from them.

588
00:50:34,726 --> 00:50:40,249
[SPEAKER_12]: We will get comments back from the state that may take more time to push this timeline out.

589
00:50:40,609 --> 00:50:46,733
[SPEAKER_12]: They submit comments for us to review the study, do some further findings that can prolong it.

590
00:50:47,654 --> 00:50:48,874
[SPEAKER_12]: From there, we have a public hearing.

591
00:50:49,615 --> 00:50:52,337
[SPEAKER_12]: At this point, the public hearing, we should have everything ironed out.

592
00:50:52,477 --> 00:50:57,740
[SPEAKER_12]: All stakeholders on board, this is a requirement, a legal requirement to hold a public hearing.

593
00:50:59,100 --> 00:51:10,508
[SPEAKER_12]: From there, if everything's hunky dory, everybody's on board, the state approves, the public approves, the affected property owners approve, we finalize these documents, we bring them for city council for adoption.

594
00:51:11,469 --> 00:51:15,912
[SPEAKER_12]: This can be about a two to three month process depending on scheduling.

595
00:51:16,940 --> 00:51:22,682
[SPEAKER_12]: And then once it's finalized and approved by the city council, we bring it to the registry of deeds to record the map.

596
00:51:23,522 --> 00:51:25,483
[SPEAKER_12]: So at minimum, this process is 12 months.

597
00:51:25,963 --> 00:51:30,825
[SPEAKER_12]: Typically it's closer to an 18, potentially up to 24 month process.

598
00:51:32,665 --> 00:51:42,648
[SPEAKER_12]: I just want to this is my last slide here, because I know we're up against it but I just want to give an example this here that we're looking at is the South Street historic district is our most recently adopted district.

599
00:51:43,429 --> 00:51:52,492
[SPEAKER_12]: I think this is a good example of what can be done where it's not necessarily contiguous or everybody that's on the street between this street and that street you're in a district we can.

600
00:51:53,552 --> 00:51:58,074
[SPEAKER_12]: I hate to use the term gerrymander because it's used heavily, but we can gerrymander districts.

601
00:51:58,274 --> 00:52:05,077
[SPEAKER_12]: What we did here, you can see between Maple and Toro Street, there's this huge block on South Street that's not included.

602
00:52:05,117 --> 00:52:16,523
[SPEAKER_12]: That's because these properties were either deemed to not be historically significant, they're more modern builds, or in some instances, property owners did not elect to be part of the district, so we omitted them.

603
00:52:17,502 --> 00:52:30,616
[SPEAKER_12]: So I think this is just a compelling visual of how a district can be laid out, especially as we're looking at Medford Square, because there's quite a bit of new mixed with old builds here.

604
00:52:32,855 --> 00:52:41,598
[SPEAKER_12]: Um, you know, so I'm here to share the process because this is being discussed as a potential preservation approach as we're looking at Medford Square.

605
00:52:41,618 --> 00:52:50,880
